<p>Control of each 'temperature zone' is achieved by balancing cooling
power (cold head) and heating power (power resistors) at the
operational set-point temperature. For additional control, the cooling
power of the cold head may be adjusted in the range 75 to 135&#160;3W
by varying the frequency of the displacer (stepper motor controlled;
40 to 70&#160;3Hz). The thermal resistances of the cooling straps have
been sized so that the complete optical bench assembly may be
temperature controlled at 290&#160;3K with the cold head displacer
running at its lowest frequency (minimium cooling power).  This
arangement minimises the heater power requirements for 'hot operation'
while maximising the cooling power (70&#160;3Hz displacer frequency)
at the lowest temperatures.</p>

<p>The Cold Optics Chamber is also used to cool a <strong>White
cell</strong> (Fig&#160;4) which is itself being used to study
absorption by gases as a function of pressure, temperature and
wavelength. The White cell contains an arrangement of three mirrors
which, by multiple reflections, simulate absorption paths comparable
to those encountered in real atmospheres. As part of the experimental
configuration, a monochromatic beam of infrared radiation from a
medium resolution spectrometer is passed into the cell through
sapphire windows. The windows are fitted to both the vacuum chamber
and the cooled White cell, while the spectrometer is supported on the
optical bench adjacent to the vacuum chamber. After multiple
reflections the emerging beam is analysed and the degree of absoption
determined for the prevailing conditions.</p>

<p>The cell has been designed to safely hold explosive and corrosive
gases, such as methane and ammonia, and at high pressures (up to
5&#160;bar) and at low temperatures (down to 100&#160;K). The thermal
design ensures good temperature uniformity (gradients less than
1&#160;K), which is of particular importance when working with gases
near their boiling point (e.g. ammonia). For high resolution
spectroscopy over more extensive conditions the department uses the <a
href="http://www.msf.rl.ac.uk/">Molecular Spectroscopy Facility</a> at
the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory.</p>
